PUP      - Weak pullup resistor to logic "1".
PDOWN    - Weak pulldown resistor to logic "0".
TUP      - Strong tieup to logic "1".
TDOWN    - Strong tiedown to logic "0".
BUF      - Non-inverting buffer.
OCBUF    - Open-collector non-inverting buffer.
OCNBUF   - Open-collector inverting buffer.
TRIBUF   - Tristate non-inverting buffer.
NOT      - Inverter.
2NAND    - 2-input NAND gate.
3NAND    - 3-input NAND gate.
4NAND    - 4-input NAND gate.
5NAND    - 5-input NAND gate.
2NOR     - 2-input NOR gate.
3NOR     - 3-input NOR gate.
4NOR     - 4-input NOR gate.
5NOR     - 5-input NOR gate.
2AND     - 2-input AND gate.
3AND     - 3-input AND gate.
4AND     - 4-input AND gate.
5AND     - 5-input AND gate.
2OR      - 2-input OR gate.
3OR      - 3-input OR gate.
4OR      - 4-input OR gate.
5OR      - 5-input OR gate.
2XOR     - 2-input exclusive OR gate.
2XNOR    - 2-input exclusive NOR gate.
2MUX     - 2 to 1 multiplexer.
DELAY    - Single time unit delay element.
DFF      - Data flip-flop with rising-edge clock.
SRDFF    - Data flip-flop with active-LOW Set and Reset.
DLATCH   - Data latch with active-HIGH enable.
SRDLATCH - Data latch with active-LOW Set and Reset.
SRFF     - Set/Reset flip-flop with active-LOW controls.
JKFF     - J-K flip-flop with falling-edge clock.
SRJKFF   - J-K flip-flop with active-LOW Set and Reset.

@{fg background}@{bg text} TTL Library @{fg text}@{bg background}

74125 - Quad tri-state buffers with active-LOW enables.
74138 - 3 to 8 line demultiplexer.
74139 - Dual 2 to 4 line demultiplexers.
74145 - BCD to decimal decoder/driver.
74151 - 8 to 1 line multiplexer.
74153 - Dual 4 to 1 line multiplexers.
74157 - Quad 2 to 1 line multiplexers.
74158 - Quad 2 to 1 line multiplexers with inverting outputs.
74162 - 4-bit synchronous decade counter.
74163 - 4-bit synchronous binary counter.
74164 - 8-bit parallel-out shift register.
74165 - 8-bit parallel-load shift register.
74169 - 4-bit synchronous up/down binary counter.
74174 - 6-bit D-type flip-flops with clear.
74175 - 4-bit D-type flip-flops with clear.
74192 - 4-bit synchronous up/down decade counter.
74193 - 4-bit synchronous binary up/down binary counter.
74194 - 4-bit universal shift register.
74219 - 4-bit x 16 RAM with tri-state outputs.
74244 - Octal bus driver with tri-state outputs.
74245 - Octal bus transceiver with tri-state outputs.
74247 - BCD to 7-segment decoder/driver.
74273 - Octal D-type flip-flop with clear.
74280 - 9-bit even/odd parity generator/checker.
7430  - 8 input NAND gate.
74352 - Dual 4 to 1 line multiplexer with inverting outputs.
74373 - Octal data latch with tri-state outputs.
74374 - Octal data flip-flop with tri-state outputs.
74521 - 8-bit identity comparator.
74543 - Octal registered bus transceiver.
7491  - 8-bit serial in/serial out shift register.
7493  - 4-bit binary counter with falling-edge clock.
7495  - 4-bit parallel-access shift register.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *        Schematic Text        *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE Text
@TOC Schematic
@TITLE "Schematic Text"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

Text can be used for general comments on the schematic sheet.  When
Text placement mode is active, the Information Box MODE line will
display "Place Text 'text'".

@{fg background}@{bg text} Text Characters @{fg text}@{bg background}

The following are the only supported characters for Text:

    @{u}GROUP        CHARACTERS            @{uu}
    Letters   A to Z (upper case)
    Numbers   0 to 9
    Symbols   #, _(underscore), -(dash)

@{fg background}@{bg text} Placing Text @{fg text}@{bg background}

New or existing old Text can used.  If new Text is desired, select Text
placement mode.  A requester will appear, and the new Text can be
entered.  Up to 80 characters may be entered.  Press "Ok" to accept the
text, or "Cancel" to not continue.  If any unsupported characters were
entered, they will be replaced by the underscore character.  Any
lower-case letters will be converted to upper-case.
  
Text placement is begun by pressing the left mouse button while the
mouse pointer is in the Sheet Box.

The last Text will be remembered, allowing the same Text to be
placed any number of times without having to reselect Text placement
mode.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *----------------------------*
@REMARK * Schematic Sheet Management *
@REMARK *----------------------------*
@NODE Files
@TOC Schematic
@TITLE "Schematic Sheet Management"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

The PROJECT menu provides several schematic sheet management options,
allowing sheets to be loaded, saved, or deleted.  A project may have
up to 99 sheets, beginning with sheet number 1.

While preparing schematic sheets, it is not necessary to begin with
sheet 1, and proceed contiguously (2, 3, etc.).  However, when it
becomes time to simulate the circuit, the Simulator program expects
there to be a sheet 1, followed by contiguous sheet numbers.

@{fg background}@{bg text} New Schematic Sheet@{fg text}@{bg background}

When the Schematic program is first started, or if the NEW option was
selected in the PROJECT menu, the schematic sheet and the Information
Box PROJECT line will be empty.  A new schematic drawing can be
started.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Save Schematic Sheet @{fg text}@{bg background}

When saving a schematic sheet, a @{" Save requester " LINK Picture_Database/Schematic.2/MAIN} may appear.  The
"Projects" button displays a list of available projects.  When a
project list is displayed, the "Projects" button is ghosted (inactive).
After a project is selected from the list, all schematic sheets for
that project are listed, and the project name appears above the sheet
list.  After a schematic sheet is selected, its sheet number will also
appear above the sheet list.  An alternative to the above method of
selecting a schematic sheet is to enter a project name and sheet number
on the text entry lines at the top of the requester.  Press "Ok" to
accept the project sheet name and number, or "Cancel" to not continue.

The PROJECT menu SAVE option will save a schematic sheet using the
project name and sheet number shown on the Information Box PROJECT
line.  In this case, a Save requester will not appear.  Otherwise, a
Save requester will appear so a name and sheet number can be provided.

The PROJECT menu SAVE AS option will always display the Save requester,
so a different name and sheet number can be provided.

If the schematic sheet was saved successfully, its name will appear on
the Information Box PROJECT line.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Load Schematic Sheet @{fg text}@{bg background}

If the OPEN option is selected in the PROJECT menu, an @{" Open requester " LINK Picture_Database/Schematic.3/MAIN}
will appear.  The "Projects" button behaves the same way as in the
Save requester.  After a schematic sheet is selected, it is loaded
immediately.  Press "Cancel" to not continue.

If the schematic sheet was loaded successfully, its name will appear on
the Information Box PROJECT line.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Delete Schematic Sheet @{fg text}@{bg background}

If the DELETE option is selected in the PROJECT menu, a 
@{" Delete requester " LINK Picture_Database/Schematic.5/MAIN} will appear. This requester is very similar to the
Save requester, but does not allow entering a project name and sheet
number.  Instead, these must be selected from the lists.  Press "Ok"
to delete the sheet, or "Cancel" to not continue.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Save Before Continuing @{fg text}@{bg background}

If the current schematic sheet was modified before selecting the NEW,
OPEN, or QUIT menu items, a requester will appear with a warning
message.  Press "Save First" to save the modifications before
continuing, or "Continue" to lose the changes and continue anyway.
Press "Cancel" to not continue.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *-------------------------*
@REMARK * Schematic ARexx Support *
@REMARK *-------------------------*
@NODE ARexx
@TOC Schematic
@TITLE "Schematic ARexx Support"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

The Schematic program supports an ARexx interface for controlling some
attributes of the Sheet Box.

  @{" Message Port " LINK Port} - ARexx message port.
  @{" Commands     " LINK Commands} - ARexx commands.
  @{" Error Codes  " LINK Errors} - ARexx error codes.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *----------------------*
@REMARK * Schematic ARexx Port *
@REMARK *----------------------*
@NODE Port
@TOC ARexx
@TITLE "Schematic ARexx Message Port"

@{fg background}@{bg text} ARexx Port @{fg text}@{bg background}

Each instance of the Schematic program will have a unique ARexx port
name, beginning with the program name, and ending with the instance
number (e.g. SCHEMATIC.1, SCHEMATIC.2, etc.).  The last line of the
PROJECT menu ABOUT requester shows the ARexx port name for the
program.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *--------------------------*
@REMARK * Schematic ARexx Commands *
@REMARK *--------------------------*
@NODE Commands
@TOC ARexx
@TITLE "Schematic ARexx Commands"

@{fg background}@{bg text} ARexx Commands @{fg text}@{bg background}

GRID SHOW/S,HIDE/S

  This command behaves the same as the SHOW GRID option in the SETTINGS
  menu.  The Sheet Box grid is either visible, or not visible.
  
COLOR DARKSHEETBOX/S,LIGHTSHEETBOX/S

  This command behaves the same as the DARK SHEETBOX option in the
  SETTINGS menu.  The Sheet Box colors are changed accordingly.
  "COLOUR" will also be accepted as the command's spelling.

NOP

  This command does nothing.  It could be used for locating a certain
  instance of the Schematic program by sending the command to see
  if it is accepted, or if an error occurs instead.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------*
@REMARK * Schematic ARexx Errors *
@REMARK *------------------------*
@NODE Errors
@TOC ARexx
@TITLE "Schematic ARexx Error Codes"

@{fg background}@{bg text} ARexx Error Codes @{fg text}@{bg background}

0  = No Errors.
11 = Syntax error in command.
12 = Unknown command.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *    Schematic Limitations     *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE Limitations
@TOC Schematic
@TITLE "Schematic Program Limitations"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

This version of the Schematic program has several limitations that
should be noted.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Editing @{fg text}@{bg background}

The only option for manipulating an object after it has been placed
is to delete the object.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Sheet Shifting @{fg text}@{bg background}

When object placement has begun, the Cursor keys cannot be used to
shift the schematic sheet view.  This means the starting and ending
points of a Wire must both reside in the Sheet Box.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Settings @{fg text}@{bg background}

The SETTINGS menu options cannot be saved.  They will be set to
default values when the Schematic program is started.
@ENDNODE

